General interval comment: Unlithified, beige, gravel size skeletal packstone with fossil molds. Neritic. Destroyed during recovery only core catcher.
This interval could be cave-in material. It is mainly composed of grainstone with echinoderms.
The remaining Section is a mudstone containing siliceous sponge spicules (from smear slide observations)
Green color, patch of glauconite 128-136 cm. With sponge spicules.
Visible fossils: bryozoan and bivalve fragment.
The lower 14 cm of the Section are paler in color and contain a bivalve fragment
Mudstone with no visible macrofossils or microfossils
Unlithified grainstone containing rare scaphopod, gastropod, bryozona, echinoderm, ocasionally hematite coated grains
Unlithified grainstone containing rare scaphopod, gastropod, bryozona, echinoderm
Unilithified siltsone with rare patch of glauconite at 60-70 cm, recognized by green color. The Section contains sponge spicules and bryozoan.
Unlithified, beige, packstone with rare gastropods, a bivalve fragment at 78-79 cm. The main lithology is either coarse silt or v.f. sand

Transition zone between packstone and grainstone mainly noticed by changes in grain size and a mixture of color. The packstone above is beige, the grainstone below is cream. It is also a zone of bioturbation. Gastropods, clams and urchin spines are present in this transition zone.
Increasing lithtification, quite litthified in the bottom also containing grains of glauconite. Rare shell fragments
Very fine grained, partially lithtified, cream, grainstone. Bryozoan fragment Rare scattered glauconite pocket at 79-81 cm.
Very fine grained, partly littified, cream, grainstone. No visible macrofossils
The upper 35 cm are unlithified, beige, grainstone likely the result of caved-in material from the Hole. Fossils are composed of urchin spines, bivalves
The upper 35 cm are unlithified, beige, grainstone likely the result of caved-in material from the Hole.
Unlithified, very fine grainstone. Contains some of the cave in material. Rare bryozoan.
Unlithified, cream, grainstone (coarser grained sand than Core 4F) with echinoderm fragments, bryozoans
Unlithified, cream, grainstone with echinoderm fragments, bryozoans

Unlithified, creamy gray, grainstone. It contains abundant glauconite and the sand is coarser grained in association with the glauconite intervals that are abundant in the Section. Possible bryozoan fragment and few unidentified fossil fragments.

Lithified gray, glauconite-rich, grainstone with abundant bivalves. Fossils present include bryozoans, gastropods, and benthic foraminferas. It also contains cavities. Only the core catcher was recovered.

Lithified gray, glauconite-rich, grainstone with abundant bivalves. Fossils presents include bryozoans, gastropods, and benthic foraminfers. It also contains cavities. Only the core catcher was recovered.
The upper 65 cm are composed of unlithified grainstone (gravel size). But the material is caved-in from the Hole. Fossils include: urchin spines, bivalves, bryozoans,
The upper 65 cm are composed of unlithified grainstone (gravel size). But the material is caved-in from the Hole.
Unlithified, creamy gray, grainstone with glauconite. Fossils include urchin spines, bivalves, bryozoan,

Partially lithified, creamy gray, glauconite rich grainstone. From 113 cm t o 150 cm the glauconite is less abundant forming bands rather than being disseminated within the sediment as in the upper 113 cm of the Section. It is also more cream rather than creamy gray. Fossils include bryozoan fragments and other unidentified fossils.

Unlithified, cream, grainstone. The glauconite exhibits a gradation to less abundance: the upper 45 cm contain bands of glauconite, several centimeters thick. The lower part of the Section contains scattered lenses of glauconite. A single bryozoan fragment is only microfossil.
void
Unlithfied, cream, grainstone with glauconite. The glauconite is lesser in abundance than in the core top.
The upper 28 cm are unlithified, gray, gravel size grainstone. Sea urchin spines are quite abundant.
Unlithfied, light greenish gray, glauconite-rich grainstone. No visible fossils.
Unlithfied, light greenish gray, glauconite-rich grainstone. The basal contact is sharp and wavy.
Unlithified, light brown mudstone with patches of glauconite. No visible fossils. The lithology is fine sand with silt.
Unlithfied, cream, mudstone, with more clay component than the interval above.
Unlithified, light brown, mudstone with glauconte. No visible fossils.
Unlithified, cream mudstone with the upper 4 cm enriched with glauconite. Visible fossils include: urchin spine and bryozoan.
Unlithified, creay gray, grainstone with glauconite. Few slightly lithified patches. Fossils: sand dollar, sea urchin spine.
Slightly lithtified, cream grainstone with little glauconite. Rare bryozoan fragments.
Unlithified, creamy gray, gravel size grainstone with glauconite. Fossils present inludeechinoderms, bryozoa
Unlithified, creamy gray, sand size grainstone with glauconite. There are patches of slightly lithified sediment especially towards the base of the Section. Sea urchin spines visible.

This Section is very soupy and highly disturbed during coring. Core 10X only recovered a core catcher with a cemented lithology. Unlithified, creamy gray, grainstone with glauconite. Patches of slightly lithified grainstone are scattered throughout the Section. No visible fossils.
Partly lithified, likely fractured during coring, light greenish gray, glauconite-rich, grainstone. Fossils present are bivalves until the last 20 cm where bryozoans become abundant.
Lithified and unlithified, light greenish gray, glauconite-rich grainstone. Abundant fragments of branching bryozoans and one benthic foram
Unlithified light greenish gray glauctonite-rich grainstone. Hemipelagic.
Only core catcher recovered, rest of core lost during coring operations. Lithified, dark greenish gray, glauconite-rich grainstone. Fossils present are: bivalves, bryozoan.
The upper 50 cm are unlithified, creamy gray, grainstone with glauconite. Sand dollars (echinoderm fragments) are common.

From 50 to 150 cm creamy gray, grainstone with glauconite and glauconite rich grainstone. Interbedded in the grainstone are up to 5 cm thick cemented intervals fractured during coring and unlithified sediments. Echinoderm fragments sand dollars up to a few cm long), sea urchin spines, large bryozoans
Partly to well lithified towards the base, light greenish gray, glauconite rich grainstone.
Slightly lithified and unlithified, light greenish gray, grainstone.
The upper 23 cm are unlithified, light greeneish gray, gravel size, glauconite rich grainstone. Fragments of hematite, sand dollars, urchin spines, bryozoan and bivalves
Partly lithified, light greenish gray, glauconite rich, grainstone. Rare bivalves, sand dollar fragments
Lithified, cream grainstone with glauconite. Contains rounded cavities probably due to bioerosion and dissolution. Thin section taken from this section. Well-preserved- 3 cm long gastropod.
Partly lithified, light greenish gray, glauconite rich, grainstone
Partly to non-lithified (from top to bottom), cream, grainstone

Partly lithified and unlithified intervals. The unlithified intervals are glauconite rich. The partly lithified intervals contain a mold of possibly a solitary coral, a few cm's long, very-well preserved. Also present are bivalves. This suggests that there was solution of the aragonite, corals, but not the bivalves. .Present in the unlithified sediment are urchins.
Partly lithified at top to unlithified at the base, cream, grainstone.
Unlithified to partly lithified, light gray grainstone with some glauconite. Tubes, bivalve shell fragments, branching bryozoans
